SIMPLE: connotation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Connotation
<hw>Con`no*ta"tion</hw> <pr>(k⟦ocr⟧n`n⟦osl⟧*t⟦amac⟧"sh⟦ucr⟧n)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>connotation</ets>.]</ety> <def>The act
of connoting; a making known or designating something additional;
implication of something more than is asserted.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>a meaning implied but not explicitly denoted by some
word or expression, which may be understood in addition to the explicit
primary meaning.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Logic)</fld> <def>the full set of necessary
properties possessed by all the objects within the extension of a term;
the intentional meaning of a term, which determines the objects to which
the term applies; the intention of a term.</def>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> intension.</syn>
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>connotational</ent>⟦br⟧
